# Entity-Component-System (ECS)

The Entity-Component-System pattern is the foundation of how OpenEdge 14 works. Everything in the game world is built using this pattern.

## The Three Pillars

### Entity
An [bold]Entity[/bold] is a unique object in the world. It has an ID and a collection of components.

[bold]Examples:[/bold]
- A player character
- A sword on the ground
- A fire hazard
- A door
- An NPC
- A particle effect

[bold]Code representation:[/bold]

// EntityUid is the unique identifier
EntityUid playerId = new EntityUid(1234);


[bold]Key fact:[/bold] An entity is just an ID. It holds no data. All data comes from components.

### Component
A [bold]Component[/bold] is a data container attached to an entity. It stores information relevant to that entity's behavior.

[bold]Examples of components:[/bold]
- HealthComponent — stores health and max health
- InventoryComponent — stores items the entity is carrying
- TransformComponent — stores position and rotation
- CharacterStatsComponent — stores STR, VIT, DEX, INT
- AI Component — stores AI behavior state

[bold]Code representation:[/bold]

public sealed partial class HealthComponent : Component
{
    [DataField]
    public float Health { get; set; } = 100f;

    [DataField]
    public float MaxHealth { get; set; } = 100f;
}


[bold]Key fact:[/bold] Components are pure data. They have no logic. Logic lives in systems.

### System
A [bold]System[/bold] is logic that processes entities based on their components.

[bold]Examples of systems:[/bold]
- HealthSystem — processes health-related events
- CombatSystem — processes attacks and damage
- MovementSystem — updates position based on velocity
- ActionBlockerSystem — determines if an entity can act
- CharacterStatsSystem — processes stat bonuses and calculations

[bold]Code representation:[/bold]

public class HealthSystem : EntitySystem
{
    [Dependency] private readonly IEntityManager _entityManager = default!;

    public override void Update(float frameTime)
    {
        // Iterate over all entities with HealthComponent
        var query = EntityQueryEnumerator();
        while (query.MoveNext(out var uid, out var health))
        {
            // Process this entity
            if (health.Health <= 0)
            {
                // Handle death
            }
        }
    }
}


[bold]Key fact:[/bold] Systems are stateless and pure. They don't store state about entities; they read/write component data.

## The Pattern in Action

### Example: Creating a Player Character

Step 1: Create Entity (get an ID)

EntityUid playerId = _entityManager.SpawnEntity("Player", new MapCoordinates(...))


Step 2: Add Components

_entityManager.AddComponent(playerId);
_entityManager.AddComponent(playerId);
_entityManager.AddComponent(playerId);


Step 3: Set Component Data

var health = _entityManager.GetComponent(playerId);
health.Health = 100;
health.MaxHealth = 100;


Step 4: Systems Process
- MovementSystem updates position every frame
- HealthSystem checks if health has reached zero
- ActionBlockerSystem allows/denies actions
- CharacterStatsSystem calculates effective stats

## Component Lifecycle


Entity Created
    |
Add HealthComponent
    |
Systems detect it (EntityQueryEnumerator)
    |
Every frame, systems process it
    |
HealthComponent value changes (damage)
    |
Network syncs to client (AutoNetworkedField)
    |
Remove HealthComponent (entity dies)
    |
Systems stop processing it
    |
Entity Deleted


## Querying Entities

Systems find entities to process using [bold]queries[/bold]. A query is "give me all entities with component X and Y".

### Method 1: EntityQueryEnumerator (Recommended)

var query = EntityQueryEnumerator();
while (query.MoveNext(out var uid, out var health))
{
    // uid is the entity ID
    // health is the HealthComponent
    if (health.Health <= 0)
        HandleDeath(uid);
}


[bold]Why use this:[/bold] Most efficient, iterates only matching entities.

### Method 2: GetComponent (Single Entity)

if (_entityManager.TryGetComponent(playerId, out HealthComponent? health))
{
    health.Health -= 10;
}


[bold]Why use this:[/bold] When you know the specific entity to modify.

### Method 3: EntityQuery (Less Common)

var query = _entityManager.GetEntityQuery();
var entities = query.ToList();


[bold]Why use this:[/bold] When you need a list of all matching entities.

## Real Example: Combat System Flow


Player clicks enemy
    |
InputSystem detects click
    |
CombatSystem.Update() runs:
    query = EntityQueryEnumerator();
    while (query.MoveNext(out var attacker, out var combatComp))
    {
        if (IsQueuedAttack(attacker))
        {
            var target = GetTargetFromClick();
            var damage = CalculateDamage(attacker, target);

            // Create event
            var damageEvent = new DamageEvent(attacker, target, damage);

            // Other systems listen to this event:
            // - HealthSystem applies damage
            // - AudioSystem plays hit sound
            // - ParticleSystem shows impact effect
            // - StatusEffectSystem applies bleeding
            RaiseLocalEvent(target, damageEvent);
        }
    }


Each system does one thing, and events connect them.

## Component Sharing Between Systems

Multiple systems can read the same component.


// In HealthSystem
public override void Update(float frameTime)
{
    var query = EntityQueryEnumerator();
    while (query.MoveNext(out var uid, out var health))
    {
        // Reads HealthComponent
    }
}

// In StatusEffectSystem
public override void Update(float frameTime)
{
    var query = EntityQueryEnumerator();
    while (query.MoveNext(out var uid, out var effect))
    {
        // Also reads HealthComponent for different purpose
        if (_entityManager.TryGetComponent(uid, out HealthComponent? health))
        {
            // Apply poison damage
            health.Health -= 1;
        }
    }
}


Both systems can safely access the same component. Changes one makes are visible to the other.

## Component Storage

Components are stored efficiently:
- Each component type gets its own storage array
- Only entities with that component take up space in that array
- Systems iterate only the storage they need
- Very cache-friendly and efficient

[bold]Memory diagram:[/bold]

HealthComponent Storage:    [Entity1, Entity3, Entity7]  (3 entities)
InventoryComponent Storage: [Entity1, Entity2, Entity4]  (3 entities)

When HealthSystem runs:
- Iterates [Entity1, Entity3, Entity7]
- Doesn't touch Entity2 or Entity4

When InventorySystem runs:
- Iterates [Entity1, Entity2, Entity4]
- Doesn't touch Entity3 or Entity7


## Adding Components Dynamically

You don't have to add all components at spawn. You can add them later.


// Player gets a health bar
_entityManager.AddComponent(player);

// Door becomes locked
_entityManager.AddComponent(door);

// Item becomes magical
_entityManager.AddComponent(item);


Systems automatically start processing the new component.

## Removing Components

You can remove components to disable behavior.


// Make NPC non-hostile
_entityManager.RemoveComponent(npc);

// Make object fall
_entityManager.RemoveComponent(entity);

// Disable AI
_entityManager.RemoveComponent(creature);


Systems automatically stop processing entities without that component.

## Component Serialization

Components persist when you save/load:


- type: entity
  id: IronSword
  components:
    - type: Sprite
      sprite: /path/to/sword.rsi
    - type: MeleeWeapon
      damage: 25
    - type: Item
      size: Large


When the entity loads, all components are re-created with their saved values.

## Best Practices

[bold]DO:[/bold]
- [bold]One responsibility per component[/bold] — HealthComponent stores health, not damage calculation
- [bold]Keep components simple[/bold] — just data and getters/setters
- [bold]Use EntityQueryEnumerator[/bold] — most efficient for iteration
- [bold]Name systems clearly[/bold] — CombatSystem, HealthSystem, MovementSystem

[bold]DON'T:[/bold]
- [bold]Store logic in components[/bold] — components are data, systems have logic
- [bold]Create tight coupling[/bold] — systems shouldn't know about each other
- [bold]Manually iterate all entities[/bold] — use EntityQueryEnumerator
- [bold]Store entity references inside components[/bold] — this breaks serialization and networking

